lized biographical information. Jacob and Wilhelm Grimm were cast as exemplars of national virtues; Hans Christian Andersen's life became—with his participation—a fairy tale in itself. Jeanne-Marie Leprince de Beaumont, the prim governess who wrote moral tales for girls, had a more colorful past than her readers would have imagined, and few people knew that nineteen-year-old Marie-Catherine d'Aulnoy conspired to kill her much-older husband. Important figures about whom little is known, such as Giovan Francesco Straparola and Giambattista Basile, are rendered more completely than ever before. Uncovering what was obscured for years and with newly discovered evidence, contributors to this fascinating and much-needed volume provide a historical context for Europe's fairy tales.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aAuthors -- Biography. 0aAuthorsvBiography. 0aChildren''s literature, European -- History and criticism. 0aChildren's literature, EuropeanxHistory and criticism. 0aFairy tales -- Authorship. 0aFairy tales -- History and criticism. 0aFairy talesxAuthorship. 0aFairy talesxHistory and criticism. 4aLiterature : Children's Literature. 4aLiterature : Comparative Literature. 4aLiterature : Folklore. 4aLiterature : Literary Criticism. 4aLiterature : Literary History. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Children's & Young Adult Literature.2bisacsh1 aBiancardi, Elisa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBottigheimer, Ruth B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCanepa, Nancy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCollinet, Jean-Pierre, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCouvreur, Manuel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHettinga, Donald R., econtribu